Cybercrime Case Study – UPI Payment Fraud

With the rapid growth of digital payments, UPI fraud has emerged as one of the most common cybercrimes, especially among students and young adults.

A typical case involves a victim receiving a call or message from someone posing as a bank official or an online buyer/seller. The scammer convinces the victim to approve a “payment request” on a UPI app, claiming it is required to receive money. In reality, approving such a request results in the victim sending money instead.

In other instances, fraudsters share fake payment links or QR codes. When these are accessed or scanned, they lead to unauthorized deduction of money from the victim’s account. Such scams often exploit a lack of awareness about how UPI transactions work or rely on users acting quickly without proper verification.

The impact of these frauds can be significant, leading to financial loss and mental stress. Due to the instant nature of UPI transactions, recovering the lost money is often difficult.

This case highlights the critical need for awareness, caution, and verification while using digital payment platforms.
